## Use Test Helpers and Stubs

**Create `*_test` packages or `package creditcardtest` for shared stubs/fakes.** (Google style: test doubles in separate package.)

```go
// ✅ Good: Test helper package
// package usertest
func NewFakeUserStore(users ...*User) *FakeUserStore {
    m := make(map[int]*User)
    for _, u := range users {
        m[u.ID] = u
    }
    return &FakeUserStore{users: m}
}

// In test
store := usertest.NewFakeUserStore(&User{ID: 1, Name: "Alice"})
svc := NewUserService(store)
```

---

## Prefer Stubs Over Mocks When Simple

**Use stubs/fakes when you just need controlled data.** Use mocks (gomock, testify/mock) when you need to verify call counts or order.

```go
// ✅ Good: Stub when verification not needed
type stubStore struct {
    user *User
    err  error
}
func (s *stubStore) GetByID(ctx context.Context, id int) (*User, error) {
    return s.user, s.err
}

// Use mock when you need: "Verify Save was called exactly once"
```

---

## Arrange-Act-Assert Structure

**Structure tests in three phases:** Arrange (setup), Act (call), Assert (verify).

```go
// ✅ Good: AAA structure
func TestProcessOrder(t *testing.T) {
    // Arrange
    store := usertest.NewFakeUserStore(&User{ID: 1})
    svc := NewOrderService(store)

    // Act
    err := svc.ProcessOrder(context.Background(), 1, 100.0)

    // Assert
    if err != nil {
        t.Fatalf("ProcessOrder: %v", err)
    }
}
```

